      <bioghist id="aspace_97738d625b770ae13109f72a3213c0ea">
         <head>Biographical Note</head>
         <p>Elizabeth Heard Bell (1908-1998) was born and raised in Summit, New Jersey. She lived in Paris for about 5 years in the 1920s, witnessing Lindbergh's landing in 1927. She married (?) Wadsworth, circa 1934, and had 3 children--Dewitt, Marcia, and Linda. They divorced and she married Stanley Bell and had a step-daughter, Ethel. Stanley Bell died in 1984. Both Elizabeth and Stanley were environmentalists associated with Montague Farm, a commune founded in 1968. They knew many local activists and were themselves anti-nuclear activists. She testified for Sam Lovejoy in the 1970s at his trial for destroying a nuclear power tower. In 1982 she published <title render="italic">Bittersweet: Poems and Prose</title>.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_b74b144406e36f2e9f5e55176a4e2a02">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Elizabeth Heard Bell papers, Sophia Smith Collection, SSC-MS-00256, Smith College Special Collections, Northampton, Massachusetts.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_091124395bee105dff5cb26c93b3bec8">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Elizabeth Heard Bell papers include correspondence, diaries, subject files, clippings, and memorabilia. The subject files include material on many aspects of environmental activism, especially against nuclear energy.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_bdd105c82258572ac48003c60950ee49">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>To the extent that she owns copyright, Elizabeth Heard Bell has assigned the copyright in her works to Smith College. However, copyright and publication of her diaries (1955-1998) will be controlled first by her daughter, Marcia Wadsworth Grimm; after Marcia's death, by her son Alvin Dewitt Wadsworth; and after his death, by her granddaughter Leslie Ann Kellogg. After her death, copyright shall become the property of the Sophia Smith Collection. Copyright in other items in this collection may be held by their respective creators. For reproductions of materials that are governed by fair use as defined under U. S. Copyright Law, no permission to cite or publish is required. For instances which may regard materials in the collection not created by Elizabeth Heard Bell, researchers are responsible for determining who may hold materials' copyrights and obtaining approval from them. Researchers do not need anything further from Smith College Special Collections to move forward with their use.</p>  
      </userestrict>
